# Roadmap

## UZArchipelago

To release a new version:
- update the version number in the CHANGELOG and Makefile
- cat the new version into gzap/apworld/uzdoom/VERSION
  (autodetection will instead detect it as <prevision version>-<build number>-<commit>,
  since we haven't tagged yet)
- rm -rf release/apworlds/zdoom_* gzap/apworld/zdoom_* && touch docs/apworld-generator.sh && make
  (this generates binaries with the right version number baked in)
- copy the apworld-generator.html to apworld-generator-<version>.html and update the links therein
- commit
- tag and push the commit
- cut the release on github using the just-generated pk3 and apworld as the binaries

### scanner

- rescan TNT with the official patch that fixes the yellow key bug
- once UZDoom releases with support for AllSkills, scan that array and use it to
  determine which spawn filters correspond to which skills.

### generator

- rethink how weapon logic works; see design/weapons.md
- progressive weapon support
  - infer the progressive weapon order from the order it appears in the wad
  - maybe pull it out as a yaml option so it can be customized
  - max_weapon_copies becomes the number of extras in the pool
  - getting extras once you have them all gives you copies of random weapons you
    already have
- treat item/key/weapon requirements as "apworld state has this item" if it's
  included in randomization at a nonzero rate, and as "location where this item
  is found would be in logic if it were randomized" if it is not included in
  randomization.
- region hierarchy refactor
  - a wad contains maps, which contain regions, which contain locations
  - maps/regions/locations are all DoomReachable and form a tree
  - in particular this means you can ask any of them "which reachables do you contain", recursively
- option to treat bosses as checks -- also needs scanner changes, highly vulnerable
  to enemy-replacement mods
  - could try placing the check in the boss's inventory, and on the ground where
    the boss would be if we can't find it
- alternate win conditions:
  - find N victory tokens
  - find N secrets
- Pass through region information in the generated pk3 (in pretuning mode or
  perhaps unconditionally) so that the region dashboard remembers its contents
  across runs even without a save file.

#### included_item_categories rework

Split it into a bunch of different options. These can use NamedRange with
something like:

    range_start = 0
    range_end = 100
    special_range_names = { 'none': 0, 'all': 100, 'vanilla': -1, 'shuffle': -2, 'start': -3 }

And then we have the following options:

    key_rando - all
    weapon_rando - all
    secret_sector_rando - none
    secret_item_rando - none
    big_item_rando - all
    medium_item_rando - shuffle
    small_item_rando - shuffle
    tool_rando - shuffle
    custom_item_rando - replaces included_item_categories

included_item_categories sticks around as item_category_overrides or similar,
and things are parsed in the order: intrinsics, then overrides, then individual
options, then fallbacks.

### ingame

- display weapons in inventory even if you don't have them
- let you hint weapons from the inventory screen
  - we have a complication for the above in that we now have two sets of weapons:
    the weapons that AP knows about and the weapons that are in the region's
    memory of which weapons you should have and are inferred from your inventory.
  - at the moment per-region weapon data is populated from the latter.
  - if we want per-region weapons we actually need two separate weapon sets per
    region, one populated by AP and one holding what those are actually inferred
    to turn into...eurgh. This needs more thought.
- hilight a level in silver if
  - when using UT:
    - new checks have entered logic since last time you visited
  - otherwise if:
    - you have received an access key for it and have not visited it yet
    - you have received keys for it since last time you visited
- Option to set requirements for whole level in region editing dashboard
- Weapon restoration doesn't always work reliably even after save/load or collecting a check, at least in TT
- Levelporting to the same map you're currently on should return you to the
  spawn point even if you have a saved location

#### Trap ideas

Zombie/Sergeant/Pinkie/Soul Trap, spawns enemies around you
Butterfingers Trap, drop all your ammo around you
Bleed Trap, slowly lose health
Acid Trap, slowly lose armour
Warp Trap, teleports you to the level start
Barrel Trap, spawns exploding barrels
Alarm Trap, activates all enemies on the level

### Hedon

Hellclaw appears only as an enemy drop in episode 1. In episode 2 it appears as
a normal weapon.

There are a lot of quest items that don't appear in the scan because they're
spawned by ACS. Logic may find it useful to define event regions, e.g. a "player has gear"
event region with prerequisites of access to the smelter and caster, having the right number
of metal bars, and having the mold.

There are a lot of quest items with a nonzero InterHubAmount. Can we pick up a
pickaxe in map01 and then be required to use it in map02? or, worse, map03, which
doesn't have a pickaxe of its own?

Bearzerk Mode sets up a bunch of actor replacements. Some of these are randomized,
e.g. a bolt mag will randomly turn into any of three different potions, a ring,
a time shard, or an armour crystal. This means we get different results each time
we scan. But, if we skip scanning that skill entirely, we miss out on any bearserk-specific
spawns!

Ideally, what we want is to, on non-Bearserk skills, scan normally, and on Bearserk,
pick up the actual replacments, e.g. `BearzerkBoltmag` in place of `Boltmag`.

MAP01 logic notes.
Spawn in hell area. Basically linear, explore to the top of the falls to get the
bloody axe key, open the axe door, go through the dream to arrive in the power
core room, get the power core, use it to power the cannon, exit to the west caves.

Note that the key is optional -- if you have the core you can skip most of this area.

Then the intended route is:
- explore the west caves, find the iron key door and broken elevator, get the iron key
- go through the iron key door, explore northwest caves, find a power core
- use it to repair the elevator and explore the barracks
- exit NE from barracks to the pond, which also opens another door letting you exit NE from pond, getting the stone key
  - collecting the scroll in the room with the stone key also opens a secret room to the north
- stone key back at the barracks lets you grab a pickaxe from the storage room
- pickaxe lets you break a bunch of walls, including one with a power core behind it
- power core lets you repair the SE exit from the barracks and go to the rest of the map

However!
- If you have the power core, you can skip the iron key entirely, exit from the barracks into the pond which also lets you access the whole behind-the-iron-key area
- If you have the iron key, you can access the north central barracks room (but not the rest of the barracks, there's a latched door!) via a secret from the pond.

So probably we do up the reachability graph vanilla-intended, but make sure that:
- barracks central north room is a separate region reachable either from main barracks, or from (secret-flagged) west pond secret
- northwest caves has a reachability link from E barracks

Setting those aside, our tree looks something like:
- west caves
  - [s] entrance secret
  - [s] tutorial skip secret
  - [pickaxe] power core nook
  - moss room
    - [s] moss room secret
  - [iron key] NW caves
    - rat room
    - [pickaxe] south time shard nook
    - [pickaxe] north time shard nook
    - NW bedroom
      - [s] NW bedroom secret
    - NW storage
    - NW gardens
      - NW gardener's hut
    - pond
      - [s] west pond secret
      - [s] east pond secret
  - [power core] barracks (probably divided into rooms)
    - north barracks bedroom
    - pond gardens (technically connected to pond, but only really reachable by exiting from barracks NE)
    - [s] gardener secret
    - [power core] battlefield

And insert additional links from W pond secret -> north barracks bedroom and from NE barracks -> NW caves.

Then from the battlefield we have:
- long cave
  - cramped caves
  - statue room
  - forest
  - forest village (divided into rooms)
  - [event] [moondrop flower] trigger moondrop secret
    - [s] moondrop secret
    - [s] secret forest
    - [s] bathhouse
  - level exit

### Faithless

deathwind city -- has another chest key in a vase, near 712,1728

### Golden Souls

Basic structure is one central hub map from which all other maps branch off. Access
to these maps is gated based on number of Golden Souls or Big Coins found, with
only map accessible initially.

Each map contains weapons, ammo, health, small coins, enemies (which drop small coins),
and one or more Golden Souls and Big Coins. Some levels contain red coins and all
red coins must be collected to reveal the GS.

For this we probably want to abandon access tokens entirely, or model them as-well-as
golden souls. This means we also need a way to say "the requirements for entering
map X are Y". It already has full persistence and a hub, so we don't need the
generated MAPINFO or even, probably, the level select screen.

Internally, we have a bunch of inventory items:
Star_Soul - golden soul
Big_Coin_Total, Big_Coin - incremented when you find a BC
BigCoinsInMap - you get one of these when in a map that has BCs
Token_BigCoinCounter - map-specific, gain one for each big coin
RedCoinsInMap, Token_RedCoinCounter - as above but for red coins

Initially progress is completely linear, with one level == one soul, and the next
level needing N+1 souls to access. As you find secret levels and big coins, though,
you can get ahead of the soul curve; secret levels contain one soul and no big coins.

There are three secret levels that must be found via exits in other maps, and three
more that require 12, 24, or 36 big coins to reach.

At 8 souls, you unlock 4 more levels all at once.

To reach the final boss, you need 15 souls; since there are only 12 "normal" levels,
you also need to do at least three of the (secret hidden + secret bigcoin) levels.

### Ashes

- Ashes 2063 reports duplicate keys because of the way keys are handled -- you
  pick up the BluePassCard and it gives you a BlueCard in your inventory, which
  the AP runtime then identifies as a new key scoped to that level, which can be
  a bit confusing but generally does not affect normal play.
